  stickyNoteInfos:
  - title: 'Push Positon:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -41.281387
      y: 710.82245
      width: 228
      height: 164
    contents: 'Sometimes, particles can be too close to the SDF surface, making them
      clip on it. We''re adding an offset thanks to the direction attribute.


      The
      direction attribute is calculated by the position (SDF) block.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: SDF Bounds SIZE
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 330.71863
      y: 518.82245
      width: 225
      height: 100
    contents: To get a proper SDF transform, don't forget to store the bounds, scale,
      and position values given by your SDF baking tool.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: 'Position SDF:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1198.7186
      y: 504.82245
      width: 295
      height: 115
    contents: 'The Position SDF block allows you to position particles randomly on
      an SDF surface or volume.

      Here, we position the particles on the surface
      of the provided SDF.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: Turbulence Noise
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1205.7186
      y: 1174.8225
      width: 194
      height: 100
    contents: This node adds a curl noise force, making particles move in random
      directions.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Conform SDF
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1184.7186
      y: 1316.8225
      width: 552
      height: 203
    contents: While the turbulence block is creating organic motion by moving particles,
      this block creates forces to attract particles and make them stick to the SDF
      surface
    theme: 
    textSize: Medium
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: Sample SDF:Direction/Gradient
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -199.28139
      y: 1933.8225
      width: 693
      height: 311
    contents: 'We need to know the gradient, or normal, of the SDF at the current
      particle position. We need this vector, as we''ll pass it to the child particles
      to properly orient them.



      To get the closest SDF gradient, we can use
      a sample distance SDF operator.

      The value is then stored in the direction
      attribute.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Medium
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: 'Inherit Attributes:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1835.7186
      y: 2274.8225
      width: 256
      height: 114
    contents: "We are inheriting the parent's position to spawn our particles.\n\r\nVelocity
      and direction attributes are used to \u201Corient\u201D the child particles.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Velocity Integration
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1787.7186
      y: 2559.8225
      width: 306
      height: 171
    contents: "The Velocity integration has been \u201Cturned off\u201D in the inspector
      when selecting the Update Context. \r\n\r\nThe Inherited Velocity attribute
      is used for orientation, but we don't want the velocity attribute to be used
      by the update context to update the position.\r\n\r\nIf you select the update
      context, in the inspector, you'll see that the \u201Cupdate position\u201D
      has been turned off.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: 'Orient:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1416.7186
      y: 3124.8225
      width: 233
      height: 125
    contents: 'The orientation is done thanks to the particle''s parent velocity
      and direction.



      The velocity serves as the alignment vector, while
      the direction is the facing vector.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Random per Strip
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 1358.7186
      y: 3360.8225
      width: 283
      height: 104
    contents: "We used the \u201Cper particle strip\u201D seed option in the random
      operator to get a random value per strip instead of a random value per particle."
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Sample SDF Parent
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 592.7186
      y: -261.17755
      width: 778
      height: 113
    contents: 
    theme: 
    textSize: Huge
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Child Trails
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 2062.7185
      y: 1643.8225
      width: 444
      height: 101
    contents: 
    theme: 
    textSize: Huge
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Trigger Event
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 899.7186
      y: 1882.8225
      width: 262
      height: 135
    contents: 'The trigger event allows you to trigger events. Those events can be
      used to spawn new particles.



      You can trigger events based on: traveled
      distance, over time, collision, etc.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: GPU Event
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: 2540.7185
      y: 1769.8225
      width: 166
      height: 100
    contents: The GPU event can be used to spawn new particles.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Create an SDF
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -80.28139
      y: 94.82245
      width: 476
      height: 334
    contents: 'VFX Graph provides an SDF baker tool that allows you to bake an SDF
      representation of your mesh inside Unity.



      You can find the tool by
      going to:

      Window>Visual Effects>Utilities>SDF Bake Tool

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Medium
    colorTheme: 3
  categories: []
  uiBounds:
    serializedVersion: 2
    x: -225
    y: -321
    width: 3059
    height: 4006
